segments.text: Interview with Sterling Morrison, November 8th, 1984.
Carl Pohlmeier interviewing.
Okay.
Should do it.
Okay.
When did you become a musician?
When did you start playing the guitar?
I started playing guitar in eighth grade.
My original instrument was trumpet, and my teacher got drafted, and I couldn't find a good one.
So I did nothing for a year.
And then picked up a ukulele.
Everybody sees them.
And learned three ukulele chords and figured, oh, well, why not try and learn some guitar chords?
Actually, my liking for rock and roll music led me to, it was just kind of a happy accident.
My teacher was gone, and therefore I was free to take another instrument.
Rock and roll would have led me to guitar playing.
I regret that I wasn't a keyboard player for my whole life.
That's the best thing to me, like John Cale.
Cale started on keyboards at three and viola at five and did his first BBC concert when he was eight and was a child prodigy.
Naturally, he did all those things for us, although we were considered a band with no talent whatsoever.
We're the most scholarship, fellowship band in the history of music, which is an oblique way of saying we're the brightest.
Not the best, but the brightest.
If being smarter than other bands could get you any place, then Velvet Underground would have gotten there.
We rarely use intelligence in songwriting or in our playing, I think.
We're not intellectually pretentious.
Only one track, I think.
The murder mystery, people might think, has some weirdness to it.
We were trying for a Joyce-ian rock and roll song.
And if you can decipher it, it's all in code, really.
It's about the history of the band.
Isn't it neat being unique?
You can hear some isolated little couplets in there.
But it's a real negative, satirical, and oblique encoded.
It is Joycean.
It's very hard to figure out just what the hell is being talked about.
But it's about the life and times of the Velvet Underground.
Same as Sister A is.
What were some early influences on guitar style?
Well, for Lou and me, and Maureen also.
See, Kel was born and raised in Wales, and then went to the Royal Academy and all that sort of thing.
So he didn't know anything about American rock and roll music, which is terrific.
That guarantees you an absolute fresh viewpoint.
John could never fall into...
conventional riff playing.
He couldn't take a lazy way out because he didn't know them.
He didn't know cliches, riffs, songs.
He didn't know any of this stuff.
Lou and I had the... Everybody says every guitar player now has encyclopedic knowledge of all this old crap.
Every guitar player has encyclopedic knowledge.
That's how you learn.
This stuff is not written down.
You have to learn it from records.
But it was straight R&B.
for Lou and me.
That's how Lou and I met.
I was playing Lightman Hopkins records, and he was in the room above.
Finally, he came lurching down, because he had a campus radio show at Syracuse, from which he got kicked off the air.
This stuff is not mainstream music.
He said, hey.
I didn't even know that he was a guitar player.
I didn't learn that for about a week.
When Lou tried to disrupt an ROTC drill, they used to drill back of the dorm.
First I heard this very loud bagpipe music blasting.
He had a good high-five set.
All us suburban kids had good high-fives.
So he was blasting the hell out of them with this bagpipe music.
And then that stopped.
And then all of a sudden I hear all this kind of humming and clicking.
And then he started blasting with his guitar.
And I said, yike.
Guitar player upstairs.
Must be that guy who won the Leidenhoff Conservatory.
And he was a creative writing major and wrote poetry and blah, blah, blah.
But identical things.
That was where the real music was.
I think things are bad now.
You should have seen the early 60s.
God, it was horrible.
Jay and the American.
There's one thing you don't have to suffer with now that we did.
It's the battle between rock and roll and folk.
A horrible, bitter thing.
You know, you remember that scene, well, pretty obvious, in Animal House, where
The guy is, I gave you my love, and all this stuff.
Then Belushi comes by, looks at him in horror, and grabs his guitar and smashes it.
Belushi, a wonderful thing.
That's my favorite scene in the movie.
I would have bashed the guitars over the head of every folk singer in America if I could have laid my hands on them.
And then, horribly, and I should have
anticipated it predictably, when the folk audience, the folk creep, pretentious audience, started to evaporate, then they just cross over.
Bob Dylan I loathe in a way that I can't express despising.
So then all of a sudden they had folk rock.
Here are these same creeps now calling themselves rock and rollers.
I just read a thing with Paul Simon someplace.
I guess it was Playboy magazine.
Paul Simon considers himself a rocker.
And he's complaining.
He said, you know, I think I've gotten a bad rap.
And people keep relating to me as a folk singer.
But I'm really a rocker.
If Paul Simon is a rocker, then so is Pat Boone.
Pat Boone was a hell of a lot more rocked out than Paul Simon.
At least Pat Boone sang Little Richard songs.
Both are hard rockers compared to Boy George.
If that's hard rock, then... Well, hard rock isn't the only rock, but you know what I mean.
By his own admission, he's essentially a balladeer.
I mean, that's his strength.
But you don't have to suffer with that now.
like rock for whatever it is, there are other problems now.
What is the real rock and roll as opposed to what is the pop schmaltz?
There was always pop schmaltz.
But among the people who really cared about what ought to be the true direction, in the 60s it was fragmented, and no music historian ought to forget that.
Some of the people thought that it really ought to be folk.
That lyrics really ought to be meaningful and socially relevant.
They're important things that can only be communicated this way.
The true rocker said, stick all that.
None of this counts.
Only grunting and shouting and howling.
Just general antics.
And I always thought that's what we were.
See, that was obviously a conflict that Lou and I had.
I was contended he was soft on folk.
because he wanted to stress lyrics.
I would make some contributions to lyrics now and again, but I constantly devalued their importance.
Not that you should have long instrumentals.
That's not a very good idea.
I've been talking about the virtues of Louie Louie since it came out.
I considered it the last true American rock and roll record.
right after Louie Louie came to Beatles.
Everybody started trying to sing harmonies and everybody tried to do this and that.
Just go back and listen to Louie Louie, what it is.
Three power chords, a garbled, possibly obscene lyric, hot Fender lead.
It was everything.
Condemned by parents and religious groups.
That's American rock and roll.
It's not a... That's why I always have
There's always a soft place in my heart for the most outrageous heavy metal bands, except when they copy each other.
In their despicableness, they're closer to the real ideal.
Barry Manilow considers himself in rock and roll.
That's rock and roll.
A rock concert is Barry Manilow.
I would like him to go to a party with Motley Crue or something.
and do everything that they do, and then see if he's still alive.
The true test of rock and roll errs, I guess, is you have to have a little physical oomph to you, at least initially.
That's why I think people ought to retire when they reach about 21.
The riggers of the road aren't playing gigs night after night.
It's partying night after night.
You get done playing at 2 o'clock in the morning and carry on until 8,
then do a TV show at 10 a.m., and then hit the plane to the next town.
That's what wears you down.
It's not not playing.
That's what keeps you alive, I think.
At least for those moments, you can't be doing anything really destructive to your body.
You can only do that when you get off.
When people are waiting in the wings to help destroy you.
A glorious way to go.
I always liked it.
I liked touring.
That's another thing that... Lou was never wild about live performance.
And still isn't.
I always liked it.
Making records is like doing the laundry.
Most studios look like laundromats.
Nowadays, I think they're a little more... you know, simpatico.
Maybe, though.
Not so much.
Some had even neon lighting.
Stuff like that.
Strange.
But anyway, to go back to influences, I would say it was black music.
I listened to old Alan Freed.
The contribution of Alan Freed isn't to be exaggerated.
Unfortunately, it was only confined to people in New York.
You had to be there to compare what Alan Freed played with what was standard fare on the radio.
He played black music.
I mean,
way out stuff, southern black music, really strange things.
Did he take payola?
Certainly.
However, there was a kind of little asterisk.
You couldn't pay him to play something he didn't like.
You couldn't pay him enough.
If he thought this is no good and it was going to embarrass him, and he had real standards about what was good, then he wouldn't do it.
But yeah, sure.
Here's a black DJ looking to make some money.
All the black artists are trying to make money.
All they ever wanted to do was be played on the white stations where the big money was and get big and famous.
And they finally did, you know, through Motown, largely.
But they've been trying for years and years and years.
They were, I guess, kind of compelled to want to try to sell out.
We were never compelled to, so we never did.
If only the last nice thing that anybody can ever say about the Velvet Underground is that we didn't sell out, that's true.
We did not.
Even if I'd known what it would take to be a top 10 or a top 40 act, I wouldn't have done it.
I was incapable of wearing a suit that matched everything everybody else wore, or choreographing dance steps, doing a little bit of light comedy on TV variety shows.
I had no interest in that stuff.
I don't want to exchange jibes with Don Rickles.
Actually, I would like to.
I suspect I would win as one of the unfunniest men.
But you know, the things that rock and roll groups were subjected to, I imagine you've seen the old kinescopes of those variety shows.
USA Network has their kind of rock history thing.
And they show old variety show kinescopes.
You're on as, OK, now for the kiddies, Ed Sullivan used to say, now for the kiddies.
And it would be the Rolling Stones or somebody, the Yardbirds.
It would be somebody good for the kiddies, indeed.
The best group in the history of Ed Sullivan was the Rascals.
Felix Cavalieri being an old friend of ours at Syracuse.
They went in for the warm-up and had the amps weighed down.
They turned everything down.
They did all their sound checks and all.
And then they went back to play the show, and they played for a live audience.
They looked at the size of the hall.
And they knew exactly what level they ought to be at for the rock and roll experience.
So they just turned all the stuff up and they played.
When I was sitting home, I didn't know any of this, naturally.
I just wanted to see how Felix was going to do on the tube.
And he did Good Lovin'.
I can't recall if they did Ain't Gonna Eat Out My Heart Anymore or not.
Great song.
But anyway, it sounded great.
And I said, boy, listen to that.
You know how live music used to sound in Ed Sullivan?
It sounded horrible.
This stuff, boy, it had bottom and punch.
I said, wow, how come they sound so good and everybody else sounds horrible?
And then when they were done, Ed Sullivan looked like he'd been struck by lightning.
And there's a big stink in the papers the next day.
They'll never be on the show again and all this stuff.
And they damaged the ears of the studio audience.
Oh, they sounded great.
They just played it like a real live rock gig.
And it sounded great.
So that's my vote for the best Ed Sullivan performance by a rock group.
The Four Tops did great one time, too.
And Reach Out, I'll Be There, has that real strong instrumental introduction.
You couldn't even hear it.
So they essentially sang a cappella the whole way.
Great, great stuff.
It was beautiful.
What nerve, what poise.
But to be a rock and roll group in the 60s was to be a strange creature.
The serious and respectable people were folk singers.
And God help us, the folk rockers.
And then there were the have to sell on the charts.
And then we had Love and Peace and Flower Power, so this would all be somehow hippie-related.
We had nothing whatsoever to do with the hippies.
Our idols were the beatniks, mine personally and Lou's personally.
Then I got to hang around with them.
That was even more amazing.
These are the guys I liked.
They were the ones who read books, wrote books, wrote poetry, played music, screwed women, took drugs.
That seemed like a good lifestyle, intellectual dissipation.
The hippies were know-nothings and do-nothings.
So I never did like them.
I thought they were harmless and kind of nice, but I wouldn't want to go live with them.
So I would say we always hung around with beatnik types and new beatniks.
They were our intellectual inspiration.
Lifestyle.
Go read On the Road again.
It's a good book.
Unfortunately, the best music they had at the time was jazz.
But all the old impulses are there.
On the Road's wonderful.
Tommy taught it here once.
Since everybody now is for Reagan, I don't know if On the Road will wash.
I forget these people don't want to do anything except get a job at the bank.
If you didn't want to get a job at the bank at the age of 21, then on the road was your kind of thing.
I worked a sperry round when I was 19.
I quit because I had a sure future.
I had free education for any place it would take me.
I was an old engineering physics major.
They would send me any place and pay all the money.
And I had guaranteed summer jobs and guaranteed employment forever and ever and merit raises and all.
And it scared me to death.
I said, wait, wait.
Help.
There has to be more things to do than this.
So I took technically leave of absence, which I'm still on.
I'm horrified by the way people are career-oriented.
And really deadly kind of careers, too.
hospital supply inventory specialist for which somebody will give you a PhD.
If you consider the courses offered at a university, not necessarily A&M here or anyplace, most have no place at all in the traditional conception of a university.
All engineering would be gone.
That's trade school.
All business would be gone.
That's trade school.
That accounts for probably 60% of the enrollment at UT.
I mean out, gone, has no place here.
And you speak to old engineering professors and they'll tell you they ought not to be here.
The engineering school ought to be someplace over there.
It's not a science even.
And anyone pretending that engineers are scientifically motivated, that person would be encouraged to get out of engineering and go into the pure science.
It's strictly applications.
It doesn't make it contemptible, but people ought to realize what it is.
I was teaching tech writing in the chemical engineering department for three and a half years.
I happen to like engineers, having been among them for a good while.
I like getting things done.
That's one side.
And the other side likes loafing and doing weird things.
What was one of your, or the biggest reasons for joining the Velvet Underground, or starting the Velvet Underground?
Yeah, we started it because we had no future in music.
We started it from a position of retirement.
And how can anybody say despair, considering how young we were?
First of all, who wants a career in music?
I didn't.
Lou didn't.
We had other things to do.
But always, while we were doing the other things, we were playing music.
Finally, we decided in 1963, this is the end.
We can't play gigs.
These people don't want to hear the songs that we would care to play, which are old R&D things.
This was before the Rolling Stones.
So the Rolling Stones started rehashing all these white R&D songs.
We just said, well, of course.
They'd always ask them, who do you like?
They'd say, oh, Bo Diddley and Chuck Berry and Little Walter and all those things.
I said, well, yeah, who else is there?
But we'd play parties in Syracuse.
People would get incensed.
They wanted to hear Frankie Valli.
They said, no, but how about It's Gonna Work Out Fine?
We were in strange bands.
We were one called 12 Screaming Niggers.
Lou and I were the two white boys.
Later it became Moses and his brothers.
Moses Williams is one of them and all his brothers and a bunch of their friends.
It was kind of hard to get the old campus gig with that sort of thing.
But it expands one's horizons, shall we say.
I grew up on Long Island.
I'm incapable of per se because of my many years among blacks.
But I discriminate among them as viciously as they do.
Not viciously, but that was another thing that I didn't like the racial attitudes of the 60s.
Oh, I just love my black brother.
Don't say that.
You don't know.
You're a black brother.
I know a hell of a lot more of them than you do.
And I tell you, these are the ones I like, and these are the ones I got no use for.
This is a worthless son of a bitch, and this one here is et cetera.
I was never shamed into liking blacks because I was supposed to.
I liked them because I did.
If I did, I had real reason for it.
They didn't like whites and never upset me either.
They had reasons for it.
I disliked usually the same whites they did.
Yeah, so it didn't make any difference.
But I thought that, I don't know what to be said about the 60s.
A time of great phoniness, but also sort of experimentation.
Some things worked, oddly.
The sexual revolution worked.
Newsweek telling me that that is over hasn't convinced me.
I don't know.
When it's over on the college campuses, then I'll know it's over.
Is it over around here?
Is it over at A&M?
It's up to the person.
That would be sad.
That would be sad.
Because it really is kind of a freedom of lifestyle now.
That has lasted.
If the youth of today is so conservative that they don't even screw, well, what can you say?
Might take a little energy out of the accounting final or something.
But that would be pitiful.
That, I thought, at least this will endure of all the 60s shenanigans.
Maybe not.
Bill Burroughs is one of my favorites.
In despair, I speak to him, and he tells me funny things about seeing this.
There's going to be a great howl when Burroughs dies.
Irreplaceable.
count the demise of Dali, which looks imminent.
Great tragedy also.
You mentioned civil rights things in the 60s and the sexual revolution.
Did you emphasize that in your music of Belitz?
No, not overtly.
I think there's an obvious laissez-faire attitude to all this.
Since, you know, the little eddies of transvestitism, S&M, and all that sort of thing, drifting through the songs, it should be understood that we would tolerate anything.
I contended that we just had all different kind of love songs.
Just kind of with some kind of love as well.
No kinds of love are better than others.
Does that mean I'm bisexual?
No, because I'm not.
I'm straight.
Was I ever under pressure to be?
No.
Was I surrounded by homosexuals and weirdos?
Yes.
So what?
Is show business and the art scene infested with homosexuals and weirdos?
Yes.
So what?
What would happen if you went to their parties?
Nothing.
Have a good time, probably.
The straights will find each other.
Others will find others.
I don't know.
I think it was good education.
Show business people are always weird.
I was reading a thing where Lorne Michaels was grumbling about the Belushi book, you know, Wired, that Woodruff wrote.
Woodruff doesn't know anything about show business.
And he isolates Belushi's behavior, thinking that this is a horrible degenerate.
And
ought to be held up as some kind of negative example.
He's not a horrible degenerate or a negative example.
In many ways, he's just typical.
Oh, he may have been a little more enthusiastic about drugs than certain other people.
All Lorne Michaels said is, look, show business is a life.
It entails different hours and different places to go and different people.
If you get up at 6 o'clock at night like Dracula and go to bed at sunrise, which indeed you will do, you have to.
Your playing schedule is going to be that way.
On the road it's going to be that way.
So what are you going to do, switch to a 9 to 5 lifestyle when you get back home?
You're up all night and you're doing things that the 9 to 5ers don't do.
And maybe you can't even imagine.
My favorite night was always Sunday night.
Always had kind of a lassitude to it.
People were totally burnt out from weekend shenanigans.
And it still had enough left in them for at least one Sunday night go around.
And whoever you saw, this was a person who didn't care about Monday morning.
Things would get real lively about 4 or 5 AM.
But that was Lorne Michaels' point, which I responded to immediately.
To Woodward, Belushi's antics were horrifying and contemptible.
He's a journalist.
A journalist who'd go to work every morning, I guess come home every night.
I don't know.
Had no sympathy whatsoever for show business.
Not that I do, necessarily.
I'm not in it now.
I don't think it makes too many demands.
After a while you cross the threshold and you can't come back.
That's what I was saying when I left.
I said, if I stick with this much longer, then that's all I'm going to be.
It puts you at a permanent remove from everybody else.
I didn't think that's necessarily a good idea.
Did you see Broadway Danny Rose?
The Woody Allen thing?
He'll have all these comedians at the beginning, comics, sitting around in a delicatessen, a stage deli in New York, talking about Broadway Danny Rose.
And then you look at his clients.
That's what show business is.
Jugglers and dog acts.
I was always horrified at show business.
It always frightened me.
that people would devote their lives to this sort of thing.
Do I like music?
Oh, yes, indeed.
Love music.
But hate show business.
Velvet Underground was never a show business band.
Just a music band.
And...
Ran around with all these theater people and whatnot.
Not that we were better.
I don't think I had enough...
I don't think I had a thick enough skin.
It really rankled me when people said something negative.
But to be a hoofer, people on stage, this takes some kind of guts.
Your ego has to be so far away and so protected that you can allow yourself to do anything.
And they do.
You know, what lies inside Joan Rivers?
God?
God, no.
Wherever it is, it's well protected.
The little essence is impervious to anything.
So I didn't think that was such a good idea, to only come out at night for life, to hang around with these strange types.
My favorite old TV show were the old Berettas.
That kind of reminded me of show business.
The sleaze element of it.
Burlesque is show business.
It has all sorts of little stepchildren.
Those old Berettas where everybody in the movie was some pimp or hooker or something.
Remember the ones that they were always trying to get kicked off?
You ever seen the early, early ones?
Oh, they're sleazy.
And he's living with his old degenerate Billy.
So that was sort of close to my conception of it.
peripheral show business life.
So why did you decide to teach English?
I was always an English major, creative writing.
Well, after I, writing and music got me out of engineering, not bad grades.
I still like, I was a ham radio operator for the longest time here.
People thought that was astounding.
I said, yeah, I like it.
Not a CB-er.
Old bonafide ham.
I'm not a computer hacker.
I bought an Apple Macintosh.
Because we get such a good price on it here.
Yeah, my roommate has some friends here who got him a Macintosh.
Yeah.
How do you like it?
Yeah, I've been playing with it a lot, too.
It's fun stuff.
Once you...
Once you get the hang of it, it does pretty well.
It's fast and efficient.
I don't know about...
I'm just using it for a word processor.
Everybody says that's like using a hammer to kill flies.
I don't have any numbers to crunch.
What am I supposed to do?
Figure out the location of the Earth's satellites two million years down the line?
I don't know.
There are no numbers that I need to run, so I'm just pushing words.
Back on the music side of it, did your bringing up electronics and electrical engineering, did that have any influence on the band or the new technology coming out of the time?
New technology is what really did it.
We built a few gizmos on our own.
And we're not afraid to make modifications on the guitars.
But I think one of the advantages
to when Velvet Underground got cranked up.
Rock music prior to then was dominated almost completely by Fendu and Ampeg in the studios, the old Gemini 2s.
Every studio in the world had a Gemini 2.
They played so many songs through Gemini 2s.
That's all rock and roll was, and it wasn't going anyplace in particular.
They invented fuzz tone, I think, around 1961.
But everybody had ways of doing that by themselves.
As I said in the biography, my amp already did it.
So I didn't need to go hear the demonstration.
The first time I ever heard it on a record was Zibbity Doo Dah, Bobby Sox in the Blue Jeans.
And I didn't care for the sound of it.
My amp, with a smooth distort, fiddling around with the preamp, that sounded better.
I was using preamp.
type things.
But then, very early on, Vox had some breadboard whiz and somehow had enough influence that whatever he drew up, they would incorporate into the amps.
And those old Super Beatles were just way, way ahead of everybody else.
Their distorters sounded better and their mid-range boost was better.
Just great
sounds came out.
It made bad speakers, so you had to put JBLs in there.
But, yeah, we had to build our own stuff, because we were on endorsement to Vox, and the latest electronic junk invented would fall into our hands.
And we would then seek uses for it.
But Cal was always busy designing this and that.
He tried a scheme to make a bass amp out of
phase linear amps and some kind of cabinets.
And it was impossible damn thing to transport.
So John, look, just take an Acoustic 360.
We ran an endorsement to Acoustic.
He said, that's a good bass amp.
We can carry it.
It'll work.
All this pile of junk here, I don't know who the hell is going to wire it up.
I don't know who's going to fix it when it dies, which will probably be two days out.
So that was that.
But yeah, we didn't really depend so much on
on our own little devices, although we did use them.
We just tried to keep abreast of who was doing what.
And also, we had long talks with them at Fox with their main guy.
He then went on and did Marshall.
He's the same character.
Left Fox, and he opted for just a pure power amp.
But you know the problems with the old Marshalls.
They were so hot.
You know, they fried themselves.
They were designed to.
The preamp was just a killer.
So if you wanted to go on the road with Marshalls, we never endorsed Marshall and never used them.
Well, I had used them.
Whenever we played with the MC5, we'd always blow up Wayne Kramer's Marshalls for him.
If you wanted to go on the road, for every one you had on stage, you had to have two others.
One was backing you up in the wings, and the other was off in the shop being fixed.
I'm not kidding.
So you needed three times as much stuff.
So at the time of the Marshall heyday, we were using sun amps because they were dependable.
Indeed, they are dependable.
How about guitars?
You've mentioned Fenders.
Yeah, the Strat or the Telecaster was used a lot back then.
Did Joe use Fender or Gibson or what else do I... Well, Lou, Lou's original guitar, I can't say it's his original.
It's the first one I ever saw him with, and I dare say it is his original.
It was an old Coco Brown Gretsch.
That's the Ostrich guitar.
And why did Lou choose a Gretsch?
Well, that was what all the black guitar players used, and Bo Diddley and all.
So he had this old, horrible-looking Gretsch.
And we pulled the frets off it, so it became a fretless guitar.
That was an ostrich guitar, modal tuned.
And I had all these old Junkers.
And an SG.
I bought one of the first SGs that came out, because it had great drive, back in 61.
I'm still very, very fond of SGs.
That guitar was stolen, but it upset me.
I'm going to have all these old fenders.
I had an old pink Paisley Telecaster 55.
It looked like vomit.
This is the ugliest guitar.
If I had that now, I could sell it for $5,000.
Nobody would believe anything this ugly could be manufactured by the factory.
It had a perfect Telecaster sound.
Perfect.
That's gone.
But I have two old Strats and a couple Fender 12s and a 335 stereo.
A good, workable guitar.
Anybody?
Are there you guys guitar players?
We both are.
Yeah.
What do you play?
I've got a Fender Mustang.
A real primitive.
Yeah.
I could have a Duosonic.
And a duosonic and a Fender Reverb amp for $200.
And I never got over there to pick it up.
This was since I was in Texas.
So you throw the duosonic away.
Patti Smith used to play a duosonic.
